  "shortBio": "Coralurges of Moonwater Coast, titled “Moonshoal Glider,” are protective tide-touched Riftlings—streamlined for shallows and surge. In the wild they stay protective, streamlined for shallows and surge, and attentive to micro-changes in brine and tideglass. Favorites include Moonvine. Their tidal lungs talent shows first as caretaking, not combat.",
  "standardBio": "Coralurge, titled among keepers as “Moonshoal Glider,” carries shifting memory in every movement. Native to Moonwater Coast, the species ebbs through brine and tideglass, leaving traces that other Riftlings can follow like soft maps. Wild groups form loose bonds rather than rigid packs; a protective individual may become the emotional center of a small hearthline. They eat Moonvine eagerly and dislike food that smells of neglect or spoilage. Ancient keepers carved Coralurge silhouettes into travel stones, believing the species guided the lost. Modern hatcheries record them as reliable companions; their practical problem-solving intelligence makes training feel like conversation. Their signature ability, Coralurge's Reef Bash, reflects a life shaped by Moonwater Coast more than by arena ambition. Many assume Coralurges are aggressive because of their tide affinity; most are cautious first. Young Coralurges practice Coralurge's Reef Bash as play long before they understand battle. Adults teach by demonstration: where to rest, what to avoid, how to share warmth or shade.",
  "fullLore": "Coralurges first condensed from residual mooncurrent along the living edges of Moonwater Coast after early Rift fractures cooled into weather. Their eggs appear where brine and tideglass gathers into stillness—never in the loudest danger, always in the pocket of calm beside it. Early surveyors mistook them for ambient phenomena until a Coralurge returned a dropped lantern, carefully, as if returning a promise.\n\nIn ancient eras, regional peoples treated Coralurges as omen-bearers rather than pets. Carvings show them walking ahead of caravans, pausing at unstable ground, and curling around children during ashfall or fog. The species was never “tamed” in the old sense; it chose. That choice culture survives in modern Riftkeeper etiquette: you do not yank a Coralurge into a bond. You invite, wait, and keep the invitation honest.\n\nModern history is quieter and more practical. Hatcheries map Coralurge care cycles with the same seriousness given to rare lines, because common does not mean shallow. Moonwater Coast still holds wild populations that trade soft greetings with passerby pets. After major Rift events, Coralurges often appear first at recovery centers—not as heroes, but as inventory clerks of comfort, counting who is cold, hungry, or afraid.\n\nNatural behavior is protective at the core and adaptable at the edges. They are streamlined for shallows and surge, companion-sized, easy to cradle, and communicate through harmonic hums. Socially, they prefer small trusted circles; strangers are assessed by scent, posture, and whether a keeper’s voice stays kind under stress. Intelligence presents as practical problem-solving intelligence. They sleep in curled nests and prefer weather that matches their affinity’s comfort band.\n\nEcologically, Coralurges act as trail markers within Moonwater Coast. Allies often include Brinepaw and Pearlurk; rivalries with Stonegrub and Groveowl are usually about nesting space or shiny refuse, not blood feuds. Predators are rare—most threats come from collapsing terrain and careless machines rather than jaws.\n\nCulture around them is affectionate and slightly superstitious. Children in border camps still leave a scrap of Moonvine on windowsills when Coralurge silhouettes pass at dusk. Collectors prize unusual cosmetics, yet marketplace notes remind buyers that verified care history matters more than glitter. The common misunderstanding remains: Many assume Coralurges are aggressive because of their tide affinity; most are cautious first. The hidden truth keepers debate in soft rooms is simpler and stranger: Coralurges can hear micro-fractures in Riftstone as a pressure change behind the ears.\n\nFrom egg to evolved form, their life story stays continuous. Eggs look like copper seed-cases veined with tide light. Hatchlings are clumsy with sincerity; adults become specialists of place; evolved stages sharpen instinct without erasing childhood habits. Battle tendencies favor supportive pulses, and evolution philosophy insists transformation should answer lived experience—not fashion.\n\nFor Riftkeepers, a Coralurge is a living chapter of Moonwater Coast. Feed it Moonvine, respect its protective tempo, and it will teach you the region’s quieter grammar: which winds lie, which stones remember, which silences are safe. Personal quests often begin with a shell symbol, a remembered scent, or a dream of a door that only opens when the bond is honest. That is the Coralurge bargain—not destiny sold at rarity price, but a life that continues because you showed up.",
